# Connector-Pair and Same-Subject Synthesis — Perspective Distinction

When adding a synthesis (ENTRY, synthesis candidate, or pattern note) about a **connector pair** or **same-subject encodings** to **more than one** CIV–SCHOLAR–[CIV] file, the text in **each** file MUST be **shaped to that civilization's distinct perspective**.

## Requirement

- **Foreground the host civilization's encoding.** In CIV–SCHOLAR–ROME, lead with Rome's encoding (e.g. continuity terminated, vessel ended). In CIV–SCHOLAR–ISLAM, lead with Islam's (e.g. arrival, imperial absorption). In CIV–SCHOLAR–RUSSIA, lead with Russia's (e.g. lost center, inheritance by default). For France–Germany connector pairs: in CIV–SCHOLAR–FRANCE lead with France's encoding; in CIV–SCHOLAR–GERMANY lead with Germany's (e.g. Alsace-Lorraine, Franco-Prussian War, Rhine corridor).
- **Other encodings as complementary.** Present the other civilization(s) as complementary encodings of the same referent — not as the lead.
- **No single neutral formulation.** Do not paste the same synthesis text into every SCHOLAR file. Each file gets a version that foregrounds its own civilization's perspective.

## Scope

- **Connector pairs:** Same subject in two civilizations' MEMs (e.g. MEM–ROME–CONSTANTINOPLE ↔ MEM–ISLAM–CONSTANTINOPLE; MEM–FRANCE–ALSACE–LORRAINE ↔ MEM–GERMANY–ALSACE–LORRAINE).
- **Same-subject N-way encodings:** Same place or event encoded in three or more civilizations (e.g. Constantinople in Rome, Islam, Russia).

## Self-check

Before writing a connector-pair or same-subject synthesis into multiple SCHOLAR files:

- [ ] Does the text in CIV–SCHOLAR–[CIV] foreground [CIV]'s encoding?
- [ ] Are other encodings clearly presented as complementary (same referent, different perspective)?
- [ ] Have I avoided a single neutral formulation copied across all files?

Reference: CONCEPT–ROME–ISLAM–DOUBLE–HELIX Section X; CONCEPT–FRANCE–GERMANY–DOUBLE–HELIX Section X; CIV–SCHOLAR–TEMPLATE Section XIV.F.
